Alot of games need to send messages around to different classes but you dont really want to have a reference to all other classes that might need the message. In this case most of the games use an kind of Eventhandler with GameEvents.
I think it would be good to add Interfaces and maybe a DefaultGameEventHandler + GameEvent for this case. That might help people to implement their own Handler or use the provided from libgdx. For this i created fully generic interfaces + a full generic DefaultEventHandler which i would like to share with you.
So here is the HandlerInterface:

``` Java
public interface GameEventHandler<I extends GameEvent<TYPE, ATT>, TYPE, ATT>{
    public void handleEvent(final I... e);
    public void registerListener(final GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT> listener,
            final TYPE... type);
    public void unregisterListener(
            final GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT>... listener);
    public void unregisterAllListener();
    public void unregisterAllListener(final TYPE... type);
    public void processEvents();
    public void processEvents(final int maxTimeInMS);
}
```

ListenerInterface

``` Java
public interface GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT> {
    public void handleEvent(final GameEvent<TYPE, ATT> e);
}
```

The Generic GameEvent which is also Poolable:

``` Java
public class GameEvent<TYPE, ATT> implements Poolable {

    private TYPE type;
    private HashMap<ATT, String> messages;

    public void init(TYPE t) {
        messages = new HashMap<ATT, String>();
        type = t;
    }

    public TYPE getType() {
        return type;
    }

    public void addMessages(ATT a, String value) {

        messages.put(a, value);
    }

    public String getMessage(final ATT name) {
        return messages.get(name) != null ? messages.get(name) : "";
    }

    public void clearMessages() {
        messages.clear();
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        String temp = "[EVENT]" + "[" + type.toString() + "][";
        for (Entry<ATT, String> e : messages.entrySet()) {
            temp += "(" + e.getKey().toString() + ":" + e.getValue() + ")";
        }
        temp += "]";
        return temp;
    }

    @Override
    public void reset() {
        clearMessages();
        this.type = null;
    }
}
```

And last but not least the default implementation:

``` Java
public class DefaultGameEventHandler<I extends GameEvent<TYPE, ATT>, TYPE, ATT>
        implements GameEventHandler<I, TYPE, ATT> {

    private HashMap<TYPE, ArrayList<GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT>>> listeners;
    private LinkedList<GameEvent<TYPE, ATT>> events;

    public DefaultGameEventHandler() {
        listeners = new HashMap<TYPE, ArrayList<GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT>>>();
        events = new LinkedList<GameEvent<TYPE, ATT>>();
    }

    @Override
    public void handleEvent(final I... e) {
        for (GameEvent<TYPE, ATT> event : e) {
            events.push(event);
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void unregisterListener(
            final GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT>... listener) {
        for (GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT> l : listener) {
            for (ArrayList<GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT>> set : listeners
                    .values()) {
                set.remove(l);
            }
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void processEvents() {
        while (events.size() != 0) {
            GameEvent<TYPE, ATT> e = events.pop();
            for (GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT> l : listeners.get(e.getType())) {
                l.handleEvent(e);
            }
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void processEvents(final int maxTimeInMS) {
        final long starttime = TimeUtils.millis();
        while (events.size() != 0) {
            GameEvent<TYPE, ATT> e = events.pop();
            for (GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT> l : listeners.get(e.getType())) {
                l.handleEvent(e);
            }
            if (maxTimeInMS < TimeUtils.millis() - starttime) {
                break;
            }
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void registerListener(final GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT> listener,
            TYPE... type) {
        for (TYPE t : type) {
            if (listeners.containsKey(type)) {
                listeners.get(t).add(listener);
            } else {
                listeners.put(t, new ArrayList<GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT>>());
                listeners.get(t).add(listener);
            }
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void unregisterAllListener() {
        for (ArrayList<GameEventListener<TYPE, ATT>> l : listeners.values()) {
            l.clear();
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void unregisterAllListener(final TYPE... type) {
        for (TYPE event_Type : type) {
            listeners.get(event_Type).clear();
        }
    }
}
```

If you like it ill provide the javadocs for it + an short explenation with using Enums for the generics. But some people might like Final static int for the Type or such so they can change it if they like. I can also create a pull request for it by the time.

What do you think about it? This gives the people using libgdx the chance to have an fully asynchronous event system. You push all events into it, and call the process() inside of the Gameloop. Actors that implement the listen interface could also queue the events and handle them on the .act(). Moreover there is a method to process for a max time if someone uses multiple Threads and want to have a fixed time for processing events. This is commen used in games and i think such guideline would be good and usefull.

