Using OrthographicCamera method setToOrtho(boolean yDown) removes screen scaling on android device. It works normal on desktop application. 
To avoid this problem I had to use setToOrtho(boolean yDown, float viewportWidth, float viewportHeight) and it worked how it should. 

Not working example on Android (works on desktop):
cam = new OrthographicCamera(320, 480);
cam.setToOrtho(true);

Working example on Android and desktop:
cam = new OrthographicCamera(320, 480);
cam.setToOrtho(true, 320, 480);

Given the class:
public class Test {
   private String name;
}

Json json = new Json();
System.out.println(json.toJson(test));

creates:
{name:Mike}

Valid json should be as so:
{"name":"Mike"}

I understand the Json class is used internally to read/write configuration files, and I understand changing this could possibly break people's existing projects/configuration files.  Anyway I was thinking it would be nice if the Json class provided a way of also producing and reading valid json.  I am currently developing a game and want to interact with a REST service.  I was going to use this Json utility but it doesn't work because it produces invalid json.

If I have time in the next week I will put something together but wanted to open the issue to see what the community thinks.
